WEBVTT

00:05.954 --> 00:06.815
how do I do this? He says, you just call a Colonel, I

00:06.935 --> 00:29.543
believe that fellow's name was, yeah, Colonel 
Green in the Pentagon and gave me the phone number

00:06.935 --> 00:29.543
and just tell him what your name is, what your 
present duty is, where you're stationed, and that

00:06.935 --> 00:29.543
you want to join the American Volunteer Group 
under General Claire Chanel. Well, under Chanel.

00:37.645 --> 00:56.052
So,

00:37.645 --> 00:56.052
next morning I called, well, in the night I started 
talking to a couple of friends of mine who had gone

00:37.645 --> 00:56.052
over to California from Florida, same base, you 
know, two of my flying buddies, Jim Cross and

00:37.645 --> 00:56.052
George Burgard. They were much younger in the Air 
Force than I did. As a matter of fact, didn't

00:59.837 --> 01:03.122
practically have a flying school. And they liked 
the idea. Dave wanted to go, and I said, well, when I

01:05.624 --> 01:09.068
call, I'll mention his name. He said, okay. And I 
was told, boy, it happens like that when you call.

01:14.394 --> 01:23.845
So I called this Colonel Green, talked to his 
secretary, gave him a name, serial number, and all

01:14.394 --> 01:23.845
that type of stuff. And that evening, I gave him the 
name of this Jim, George, Burgoyne Jim Cross. That

01:35.088 --> 01:37.811
evening, there was a wire received from 
headquarters. An old colonel, he was a major then,

01:37.831 --> 01:43.178
Dias, D-I-A-Z, I'll never forget it. He called me 
in, and he said, Bob, what in the hell is this wire

01:43.198 --> 01:47.383
I've got? He says, I'm giving instruction to 
release you from active duty and reserve duty

01:48.103 --> 02:01.760
immediately, and here's your order sending you to 
your home for subsequent release to go on another

01:48.103 --> 02:01.760
mission. He said, what the hell is this all about? 
So I told him. Boy, he was madder than hell. He said,

02:06.516 --> 02:07.958
well, why don't you talk about it? I said, well, I 
didn't have a chance. It was one of those things

02:09.140 --> 02:11.624
that came up. He was mad to lose you. Oh, yeah. One of 
his key men. Same way as them. They had orders, too.

02:17.734 --> 02:18.776
Yeah, they got orders, too. Matter of fact, the 
same wire had all three names. But I was a flight

02:21.140 --> 02:23.824
leader, so that's what he called me. But he 
eventually understood and didn't hold anything.

02:28.932 --> 02:31.977
It took about, well, I was gone in about 48 hours. So 
you were out in L.A. at this time. And they paid my

02:36.711 --> 02:38.735
way home with dollars. They did. And I was given 
instructions, subsequent instructions on

02:39.596 --> 02:45.185
telephone from Colonel Green's office. I guess 
Colonel Green was a contact point. I had the

02:47.148 --> 02:50.333
project in the munitions building. Sure. And I was 
just told to go home and stay there until they

02:51.335 --> 02:58.086
contacted me. They figured I'd be around.

03:02.720 --> 03:13.718
And so I went home, and got a telephone call to 
report to San Francisco on September the 21st,

03:02.720 --> 03:13.718
1941. And that was about two weeks off. And they 
sent me an airline ticket, and I packed up my stuff

03:18.947 --> 03:27.261
and went to San Francisco. And I forget what hotel.

03:32.673 --> 03:34.515
buddies to be and a lot of other guys. As a matter of 
fact, there was about thirty-five of us on this

03:34.535 --> 03:37.438
contingent. There had already been two 
contingents shipped over. And we were to go over on

03:40.601 --> 03:53.574
the Bosch Fontaine, a Dutch motor ship, to 
Rangoon, Burma by various different means. It was

03:53.594 --> 03:54.254
a freighter? No, it was a—well, it was a—they call 
it a motorboat because it was propelled

04:02.643 --> 04:05.887
steamship, really. Well, it wasn't steam, it was 
oil propelled. Diesel. Diesel, yeah. But they

04:09.451 --> 04:13.256
call it the USS Boche Fontaine. It's the bottom of 
the ocean now, by the way. Some of the Japanese

04:14.898 --> 04:16.179
subsequently. It was quite a motor ship. It was 
diesel powered. And it was strictly passenger,

04:20.785 --> 04:23.928
some freight. They carried freight. Well, I say 
it's a combination. And about 35 of us guys Two

04:29.963 --> 04:39.517
contingents, as I said, had already gone over, and 
we were to go to Tongu, Burma, right in the central

04:29.963 --> 04:39.517
part of Burma, by way of Rangoon. And it was going to 
take us, but it so turned out we sailed on the 25th of

04:39.537 --> 04:50.593
September of 1941, and we docked at Rangoon 
October the 12th. Wow, that's a long time. That

04:52.495 --> 04:53.116
long. We went to Hawaii, and then from Hawaii we 
sailed due south for a long, long time. And I said,

04:59.680 --> 05:07.791
well, I found out even aboard ship that we were 
boarding the Japanese shipping lane for obvious

04:59.680 --> 05:07.791
reasons. This was a Dutch, you know. Sure. This 
goes back to, I think, I initially made the comment

05:10.275 --> 05:13.239
to you. I think it was Christmas Island we sailed 
right by. We saw it one day. But boy, it seemed like

05:18.326 --> 05:25.596
we were on that boat forever from Honolulu to 
Surabaya, Java. That was the first stop. Well, we

05:27.258 --> 05:28.540
picked up a pilot. off of Sydney, right here. No, 
Townsville. Picked up a poly right off

05:35.721 --> 05:41.808
Townsville, Australia, and we came on back down 
and sailed and came into Surabaya, Java. And it was

05:42.749 --> 05:53.802
there, Surabaya is quite a Dutch port, and we could 
see fortifications being put in then.

05:59.367 --> 06:02.191
against the Japanese.

06:04.816 --> 06:06.458
My passport, I was a clerk. Is that what it said on 
it? I had to sever. As a matter of fact, I even had to

06:09.984 --> 06:12.768
resign my reserve commission. Oh, okay. I wanted 
to know about that. What happened as far as the U.S.

06:14.390 --> 06:17.796
military is concerned? Because you were really 
getting out of the service. As a matter of fact, I

06:20.520 --> 06:26.910
was told through this Colonel Green's office that 
when you come back,

06:36.695 --> 06:38.757
But would you lose time? No. How did that work? 
Would you lose time and grade? I had to get out. I had

06:45.363 --> 06:47.565
to resign from the service. And he gave me an 
honorable discharge. And I also had to resign my

06:50.928 --> 06:57.454
reserve commission, which was sort of an unusual 
thing. I had to reserve all relations with the U.S.

06:57.654 --> 07:02.198
military. And upon return, I would be reinstated 
with my reserve commission, and it was debatable

07:04.741 --> 07:16.999
for longevity purpose of entity pay whether that 
one year would be held out or not. But

07:17.820 --> 07:28.777
subsequently, I was found out that they did not 
give me credit for that one year of service on my,

07:17.820 --> 07:28.777
figured my longevity pay. But my commission was 
dated back The day I got out of the service was

07:32.888 --> 07:46.485
actually, it was dated back to

07:32.888 --> 07:46.485
September the 20th, sometime in September. When I 
re-entered the service on October the 9th, I

07:47.387 --> 07:55.918
think, 1942, no, 43,

07:47.387 --> 07:55.918
when I got back home. 41, no wait, 42.

08:03.230 --> 08:17.164
My reserve commission was dated back to make it 
continuous, but my active duty service was picked

08:03.230 --> 08:17.164
up the day I returned to the military, so it got me 
here. And I went back, by the way, as second

08:17.184 --> 08:20.107
lieutenant. One week later, I was promoted to 
captain. Another week, I was promoted to major.

08:24.291 --> 08:26.113
The following week, I was promoted to lieutenant 
colonel. It was that understanding when I went

08:27.575 --> 08:30.958
back to the service. Well, what do you mean that? 
Well, I'm getting way ahead of myself. This is when

08:34.541 --> 08:36.724
I got out of the Flying Tiger and came back home. 
They tried to induct us over there, you know. No. To

08:41.911 --> 08:43.133
stay right on the job. But the way they were doing 
it. Well, we'll get to that. Let's get to that. But

08:48.340 --> 08:50.463
now let's go. I just wanted to find out the legality 
of how the service would allow one of their own

08:50.503 --> 08:57.232
pilots to become a volunteer. And then what would 
happen? to have a military career. Well, I dare say

09:02.303 --> 09:10.210
all of this was foreseen by the administration 
from the president on down. Look, we know we're

09:10.250 --> 09:12.953
going to be in a war with the Japanese. I've heard 
subsequently through political channels,

09:12.973 --> 09:27.827
diplomatic channels, subsequently in Russia, 
you know, amongst discussion with ambassadors

09:12.973 --> 09:27.827
and all, for instance Harriman, that Roosevelt 
supposedly made the comment that One of the

09:28.600 --> 09:35.371
greatest solutions to one of the most difficult 
problems he ever had was when the Japanese bombed

09:28.600 --> 09:35.371
Pearl Harbor. It made it simple for him. He just 
declared war on them. And he knew all along,

09:38.777 --> 09:43.505
eventually, he was going to be confirmed with the 
task of declaring war against Japan. But this made

09:44.266 --> 09:46.149
it simple. I don't know how true that is. And I would 
be a bit surprised if he made that step. Anyway.

09:53.441 --> 09:54.102
So you got? You were in the Far East. They knew 
they'd eventually take us over as part of the Air

09:55.520 --> 10:02.950
Forces of, let's say, the Far East. They knew 
they'd take us back. And was the understanding

10:03.670 --> 10:11.620
that you could sign up for as many one-year tours of 
duties with Chenault and Spalding Tigers as you

10:03.670 --> 10:11.620
wanted? Yeah, but the initial thing was for one 
year. The contract was for one year, and then if we

10:15.105 --> 10:19.590
continued on, you could sign up for another year. 
Your pay was a lot better. Oh, I was getting about,

10:21.372 --> 10:23.515
if I remember correctly, I was doing, as a second 
lieutenant in the Air Force, I think I was doing

10:24.052 --> 10:27.235
$100,000. You were a first lieutenant now. That's 
why I was doing $162 a month. $162 as a first

10:31.059 --> 10:32.841
lieutenant? Versus $600 a month. Plus $500 for the 
airplane. Plus all the expenses. I didn't have to

10:39.067 --> 10:43.111
pay any money for any food or lodging. And, of 
course, I was being trained in combat real estate.

10:48.937 --> 10:51.139
What was it like, and where were you sent? What base 
did you finally end up at? The base, the initial

10:56.297 --> 11:13.903
training base, in the middle of, well, actually 
the first continued arrived in June of 1942 at

10:56.297 --> 11:13.903
Tongu, Burma, T-O-U-N-G-O-O, right in the middle 
of the center of Burma at an RAF.

11:21.072 --> 11:26.399
They had the major control and influence in Burma. 
As a matter of fact, they had- They were the British

11:26.419 --> 11:29.363
Empire. Right, that's right. And they had three or 
four air bases on them, one of which was Tangu. Just

11:34.851 --> 11:42.862
a little tarmac strip, tarmac, British, is a 
mechanized strip about 2,000 feet long with a one

11:34.851 --> 11:42.862
hanger. That was their training base. Somehow or 
other, through Lend-Lease, and I don't know the

11:47.245 --> 12:02.783
story of this, but the Chinese with the British 
agreed to let Chenault use this base in Burma to

11:47.245 --> 12:02.783
train the American Volunteer Group. That's what 
it was called, American Volunteer Group. We

12:05.085 --> 12:08.870
didn't even know what Flying Tiger was at that 
time. And I think he was given a year to train the

12:09.651 --> 12:16.138
group and then move it up to China. after we were 
trained. He wanted freedom to train. See, bases in

12:18.880 --> 12:21.903
China were being bombed at that time. So he wanted 
freedom to train us. But one of the stipulations

12:24.226 --> 12:32.315
was, and the freedom he was given, he chose the most 
experienced and capable pilots he could get. He'd

12:32.935 --> 12:34.717
ask for the best. He got the cream of crop of 
maintenance people, armorers, communications

12:35.178 --> 12:46.210
people, all the logistical support types, 
airmen, Many of the guys were master sergeants of

12:47.067 --> 12:50.232
that type. Their pay was ordinarily increased. 
And nine-tenths of the guys were fighter pilots.

12:57.942 --> 13:02.108
The Navy, the Army, the Army Air Corps, and the 
Marine Corps. I think there were four Marine

13:02.128 --> 13:04.812
Corps. All of them were. Well, some of the guys in 
the Navy were bomber or attack pilots. And I was

13:10.160 --> 13:12.383
accepted.

13:19.383 --> 13:25.069
When Ault had it planned at that time, he had 
dreamed of really studying the entire Air Force

13:19.383 --> 13:25.069
and getting some bombers. Ultimately, when he had 
the 14th Air Force inducted into the service of the

13:25.389 --> 13:34.860
general, the United States Air Force, then he did 
get some bombers over there. And they visualized

13:34.880 --> 13:38.984
me being head of the bombing section when they got 
some B-17s. And, boy, I dreamed of that. But in the

13:40.926 --> 13:44.590
meantime, I was getting back fighters, P-40s. I'd 
never flown a P-40 in my life. OK. How about the

13:46.272 --> 13:47.533
training? So we arrived at Tongu by train from 
Rangoon, and some of the boys had been there

13:47.733 --> 14:00.531
already, met us, took us out, put us up in the 
barracks, and we started our training. How many

14:01.532 --> 14:02.353
were you? The initial plan, ultimate plan, was for 
100 pilots with 100 airplanes with a small staff

14:03.354 --> 14:16.913
for the group under Chenault himself, probably 
15, 20 staff people. and about 250 officers and

14:17.517 --> 14:25.745
officer types and airman types. Total of about 275 
in the entire group. That's 275 Americans. This is

14:31.490 --> 14:40.819
tantamount, this would be tantamount to a wing, a 
fighter wing in the United States Air Force, which

14:31.490 --> 14:40.819
on an ordinary base is around 4,100 people. But, 
now you see, we would just be the tactical outfit

14:40.839 --> 14:46.444
that would fly up to China and be imposed complete 
logistical organization of the Chinese Air

14:46.897 --> 14:58.109
Force, where they provided the messing, the fifth 
echelon maintenance and supply, and all of that

14:46.897 --> 14:58.109
stuff. So was Chenault there when you arrived? 
Chenault was already in China. Was he training you

15:05.337 --> 15:08.101
down there? Oh, yeah. His main office was in China, 
Kunming, China. We arrived, and well, since June,

15:14.150 --> 15:26.942
when the first contingent arrived, Tom Goo, he'd 
been spending most of his time at Tom Goo, you know,

15:14.150 --> 15:26.942
personally, with a few of his staff supervising 
the training. And as he received us, you know, he

15:27.822 --> 15:43.937
gleaned over our records and so forth, and picked 
the better qualified people for the certain key

15:27.822 --> 15:43.937
staff, and then as he learned more about certain 
people, you know, maybe this guy was more of a

15:27.822 --> 15:43.937
communicator than he was a pilot, he may have 
pulled him, put him in the communication. key

15:44.558 --> 15:46.881
staff members, like a material man. One guy living 
out here in Abilene, Texas right now, Pepe Paxton,

15:48.182 --> 16:01.819
he turned out to be, well, he had an accounting 
degree and he was quite a financial type of guy, and

15:48.182 --> 16:01.819
he wasn't a pilot at all, to tell you the truth about 
it. And he was a little bit older than the rest of us,

16:01.879 --> 16:06.825
so he made him his finance officer, that type of 
stuff. So we had a going organization. How good was

16:09.228 --> 16:10.209
the training? The training was, the training per 
se, I'd say was medium to good. It wasn't the best in

16:21.324 --> 16:33.098
the world because I'd say 98% of the pilots that 
came over had never flown a P-40 before. There'd

16:33.259 --> 16:37.344
only been one or two, I think, guys that had flown a 
P-40 before out of the airport. Langley Field had

16:37.364 --> 16:40.447
just gotten some P-40s, I think. And the rest of us 
were from other types of airplanes. The few who

16:45.882 --> 16:48.586
would talk, then they taught others, and they 
taught others. So the training really wasn't a big

16:48.646 --> 16:53.352
problem. We were elite. We were already trained 
people. For instance, I was a bomber pilot. You

16:59.159 --> 17:01.482
were getting used to the P-40. That's right. Being 
indoctrinated into, in other words, I was being

17:02.203 --> 17:07.610
re-equipped with a new airplane. I had one in mind, 
too. So you go on just training flights? Training

17:12.917 --> 17:15.180
flights, get indoctrinated, and... I had to rush 
through things. Sure. How long did you train?

17:22.756 --> 17:30.068
Well, if I remember correctly, I think I had my 
first flight about the first of November. I had

17:30.088 --> 17:35.577
about twelve hours in the P-40 on December 7th, 
when Warbrook moved. But I had already been on

17:35.597 --> 17:43.429
several, oh, many combat missions where doing 
actual, you know, engaging in aerial combat

17:47.780 --> 17:55.408
Matter of fact, I was, for the latter part of 
November, I was teaching some newcomers fighter

17:47.780 --> 17:55.408
tactics and P-40s. I'd been on gunnery missions. 
I'd never flown a gunnery mission, air-to-air

17:57.330 --> 18:00.714
gunnery mission. My first mission was against 
Japanese bomber on December the 18th. But I had

18:04.518 --> 18:06.660
done ground gunnery with a P-40. I hadn't gotten to 
the point where I did air-to-air gunnery, as a

18:07.000 --> 18:10.003
matter of fact. What did you think of the P-40? I 
loved it. As a matter of fact, first thing, I was

18:13.627 --> 18:15.289
back in the fighter. And it was an inline engine, 
you know, and looked sleek, powerful. You could

18:24.685 --> 18:29.551
turn a vertical dive and just go all out and never 
worry about anything coming loose. It'd

18:29.651 --> 18:35.519
terminate around 450-something like that miles 
an hour and hold together. How could you compare

18:35.920 --> 18:40.126
it, or would you compare it with the Japanese 
airplanes? Well, that's what I'll get into, if

18:40.146 --> 18:42.349
it's okay. Yeah, I'd like to do that. I didn't meet a 
Japanese zero until Van Goon in February. But I had

18:50.590 --> 18:52.754
utmost confidence in it. And the key thing, 
though, was the knowledge that Chenault had of

18:52.874 --> 19:02.549
Japanese zeros and Japanese tactics as a result of 
being in China so long. He personally taught the

19:03.310 --> 19:10.120
first guy that came over to the first contingent, 
and then, you know, he used them to teach us. But

19:10.781 --> 19:13.305
even at times, he'd come in and give us talk. 
personal talks. And we had pictures of the Zeros,

19:15.331 --> 19:21.557
and then the old man here, his personal 
experience. We were completely confident of what

19:21.577 --> 19:25.741
he was telling us. And we were given, you know, he 
was the master of the flying in pairs, too. He

19:34.810 --> 19:36.892
developed those tactics in the United States Air 
Force. He's a master of that right now throughout

19:37.012 --> 19:41.757
the entire Air Force of the world. always be at 
least two planes together. And

19:45.453 --> 19:55.307
he knew the characteristics, flat 
characteristics of a P-40 compared to Zero. Zero

19:55.808 --> 20:00.054
is an extremely maneuverable aircraft, very 
light. The first one may have had no armor,

20:01.316 --> 20:05.102
protective armor in them at all. And it had two

20:05.923 --> 20:11.271
7.2 caliber guns in them, a little bit less than a 
.30 caliber. We had two, we had four .30 calibers

20:16.204 --> 20:26.554
and a wing root of the P-40B, the first one we had, 
and two .50 calibers and a fuselage shooting

20:16.204 --> 20:26.554
through the propeller. And we tried to cock the .50 
calibers in a cockpit yourself, just manually.

20:35.022 --> 20:39.547
You know, the butt of the gun sticking right out in 
front of your shoulder. Whereas the the 430s and

20:41.457 --> 20:53.215
the wings, you cocked and primed with hydraulic 
buttons.

20:53.236 --> 20:54.858
Firepower, then. Oh, yeah. Oh, we had superior 
firepower. We had superior speed, definitely in a

20:57.082 --> 21:02.470
dive. What about flat out? Flat out at altitude, we 
were just about equal. As a matter of fact, at

21:10.700 --> 21:15.184
extreme altitudes, 0 to 21,000 feet, we were sort 
of at a disadvantage of zero. We were a little bit

21:15.204 --> 21:16.965
faster. But in a dive, the zero would have a 
terminal dive that was slower than us. We were out

21:23.912 --> 21:26.174
diving. But we wouldn't dare turn with it. So we 
were given a tactic to use against the zero. That's

21:33.685 --> 21:36.008
what we practiced and trained with. You couldn't 
turn as fast as that? Every turn, come in, hit and

21:37.550 --> 21:41.456
run tactics. Hit and run tactics, keep up a high 
airspeed, and of course you could come in in the

21:41.636 --> 21:59.441
initial attack with a superior altitude, hit and 
break off, then go out, then come back, trying to

21:41.636 --> 21:59.441
reclimb into the altitude. Try to maintain 
altitude, though. and stay away from them from the

22:01.175 --> 22:04.980
standpoint of horizontal maneuvering. And if 
they do happen to get on your tail, split us out and

22:05.561 --> 22:12.830
go into a high-speed dive to pull away from them. 
And that's the way we fought them. And I have nine

22:16.274 --> 22:21.421
and a quarter victories. I'm almost a double ace. 
Well, we're going to get to that. We're going to get

22:26.127 --> 22:29.511
to those victories. But I wanted to know now about

22:29.930 --> 22:39.281
when was your training completed? Let's get back 
to the narrative. My training wasn't completed.

22:46.470 --> 22:55.260
And many of the pilots in my contingent, as a matter 
of fact, I think, if I remember correctly, there

22:46.470 --> 22:55.260
was one or two pilots that had not taken back. Every 
pilot, we had about 15. 68 pilots at that time might

22:58.634 --> 23:24.405
continue came over at about the 68th pilot there 
was one more contingent the incident was in route

22:58.634 --> 23:24.405
and got just about the wake island on december the 
7th and they turned it around saying back home that

