would have included the other 32 policies you 
would have had your hundred right but they sent

22:58.634 --> 23:24.405
them back home but so we started out with 68 pilots 
And at that time, we probably had about 50 of the

23:24.942 --> 23:35.632
airplanes, 55 or maybe 60 of the airplanes, of the 
100 P-40. And I had, like I said, I think I had 12

23:36.993 --> 23:39.295
hours. And I have an old Chinese log book that I 
still keep. So you had 12 hours of training. 12

23:45.721 --> 23:52.907
hours of NAP-40 total on December the 7th, which 
included some gunnery missions. See, I had a total

23:53.275 --> 23:55.097
of about... When was your first mission? You mean 
actual combat? Yeah. When were you first sent out

24:00.281 --> 24:05.385
to engage the enemy, if you did or not? On December 
the 7th. Of course, we went on December the 7th. We

24:10.129 --> 24:11.110
got the news. Pearl Harbor was hit and all of us were 
shocked. Well, we immediately worked all night

24:12.832 --> 24:17.796
long, armed our guns full up. We were ready to go to 
work because we thought we were going to be hit four

24:17.816 --> 24:21.539
days over. And we immediately went on alert. In 
other words, you were not hit at all, your air

24:23.617 --> 24:27.222
bases? No, no. Even though they were out? Oh, okay. 
Oh, they knew exactly what we were doing. Oh, yeah.

24:32.730 --> 24:35.554
Matter of fact, they knew we were polished when we 
came through Surabaya. This stuff came out in the

24:35.574 --> 24:39.680
papers, the Japanese in the papers. We know about 
the American Volunteer Group that continued

24:40.000 --> 24:45.548
coming through on the way to China, I mean to Burma. 
We know where they're based and all, and said, you

24:46.008 --> 24:49.734
know, eventually we'll take care of it. But they 
were busy hitting Singapore, Philippines, They

24:53.165 --> 25:02.254
had no respect whatsoever. They didn't even worry 
about American volunteers. They figured, you

25:06.699 --> 25:13.406
know, that we were a polyglot mercenary outfit and 
that we probably wouldn't be able to find our way

25:06.699 --> 25:13.406
out of a paper bag. We learned this subsequently. 
Well, we went on alert, and of course, like I say, we

25:15.608 --> 25:22.615
were expected to be hit, but we They went to some, 
you know, Pearl Harbor, all hell broke loose. The

25:26.943 --> 25:30.268
United States was in a war, and then of course we got 
in a war against Europe, too. I mean, active power.

25:32.592 --> 25:37.639
Well, the fat was in a fire then, so some high-level 
conferences. This pushed up the schedule for

25:38.620 --> 25:42.105
Chenault considerably. And after some 
consultations with the British and the Chinese,

25:48.295 --> 25:50.138
Not the American, but the British and Chinese. 
Well, I guess America had to be in, because of the

25:50.158 --> 25:59.050
Lend-Lease airplane and all, but to my knowledge, 
it was primarily between the British and the

25:50.158 --> 25:59.050
Chinese. One of our squadrons, we had three 
squadrons, 1st, 2nd, and 3rd Pursuit. One of our

26:07.543 --> 26:18.218
squadrons, I think it was 3rd Squadron, would go 
down to Rangoon with the idea of protecting the

26:07.543 --> 26:18.218
port for the Burma Road to push the client into 
China. The other two squadrons would immediately

26:18.923 --> 26:28.354
deploy up to Kunming, China, our main base that was 
being prepared for us in China, where we were all

26:18.923 --> 26:28.354
supposed to have gone. The whole group should have 
gone, planned where. And we were going to go, I

26:31.938 --> 26:37.085
think, planned where in the early part of 1942 we 
would have gone to. Is that right here? Yes, yes.

26:42.111 --> 26:44.213
Sorry, our error. Here's Kunming right here. Tom 
Boo is right here just south of Young Yim here, and

26:48.303 --> 27:01.723
south of Mandalay, and that's where we were 
training here at Rand Goodman. And so you flew up

27:02.004 --> 27:03.486
and over there? Up and over the hump, that's the 
north part of the hump. And when did you fly over the

27:06.671 --> 27:08.694
hump? In December, we deployed up to Kunming on the 
14th December 1941, and on the 18th of December

27:16.450 --> 27:26.203
1941 was my first taste of combat. Okay, now before 
we get into the first taste of combat, tell me about

27:26.563 --> 27:31.810
flying over the hump. Well, on that route from 
Canggu

27:40.615 --> 27:44.520
northwest to Kunming, you really don't fly over 
the hump. The real hump is between India and China.

27:50.367 --> 27:52.950
And of course, I've flown over that. But you just 
have no, in those days, no navigation aids

27:52.970 --> 27:57.796
whatsoever. In our P-40, we had that old 
commercial radio set for air-to-air RTT. but we

28:07.312 --> 28:09.154
had no nav aids whatsoever. The only thing we used 
was a map, and I learned to navigate all over China

28:09.454 --> 28:19.603
and Burma and India by nothing in the world was 
flying the contours of the mountains. The first

28:19.923 --> 28:25.107
time I ever flew over the hump was a P-40 with no 
contacts, I mean no nav aids. The first time you

28:25.127 --> 28:26.629
flew what? Over the hump. Oh, okay, over the hump. 
Actually, the first time I ever flew over the hump

28:29.751 --> 28:36.137
was in a P-43 later on, which I was India into China. 
But you might call this a partial flight over the

28:38.858 --> 28:54.481
southern part of the hump, because we did fly up by 
way of Lashio, which is just south of the Chinese

28:38.858 --> 28:54.481
Burma border, then almost due east to Kunming. So 
you do fly over the southern part of the hump, and

28:54.501 --> 29:03.154
it's just a forbidding area, no roads, no nothing, 
except you see the Burma, the Burma Road being

29:03.590 --> 29:11.464
built along the mountain to supply into China, 
southern China, because the Japanese blocked off

29:03.590 --> 29:11.464
the rest. Now that's where all the elite support 
was to go to China, that Burma Road. And that's what

29:15.371 --> 29:17.395
we were supposed to protect. Instead, that was 
supposed to be the mission of the American

29:18.357 --> 29:25.710
Volunteer Group, protect the Burma Road from the 
Chinese. I mean from the Japanese attack. Now,

29:29.206 --> 29:33.933
what were your feelings when you knew that you were 
now finally en route to combat? Just sheer

29:34.073 --> 29:37.819
excitement and eagerness. I was ready and hot to 
try. I just couldn't wait. How about the

29:42.546 --> 29:45.430
excitement of your other 68 colleagues? No, not 
68. Because a third of them went down south. Oh,

29:49.476 --> 29:50.157
they were. Did you have about 40 that went up with 
you? Yeah, about two-thirds of us went up. They did

29:55.245 --> 29:58.690
about three waves. The happier ones were the ones 
that went to Rangoon because they figured they

29:58.838 --> 30:06.150
were going to get to combat before we would. And 
they were much more excited. It so turned out that

30:08.894 --> 30:15.244
we, who went to Kunming, actually got the first 
take to combat. But within a few days, they at

30:15.325 --> 30:21.454
Rangoon really got involved in combat. As a matter 
of fact, it was the 24th of May. 23rd, 24th, just for

30:23.746 --> 30:25.809
Christmas. They really got tangled up, and from 
then on, it was every day that way. But you were

30:31.197 --> 30:32.139
excited. Oh,

30:32.179 --> 30:36.545
all of us were. We felt we were trained. We were 
confident.

30:43.495 --> 30:53.230
I felt like a highly trained, hot-to-trot, 
typical American Air Force fighter wing pilot.

30:53.480 --> 30:55.603
fight upon it. We were confident. We just couldn't 
wait to get in the fight, and particularly since,

30:57.525 --> 31:03.093
you know, they hit Pearl Harbor. Oh man, you know, 
we were fired up. And to me, a Jap was a savage, and

31:06.157 --> 31:09.721
there was only one way. Kidding. We were ready. 
Really excited. So, we just couldn't wait. And

31:18.893 --> 31:21.917
every minute that particularly when we get the 
Jimba, which is a Chinese air raid one, Jimba, air

31:22.437 --> 31:32.311
raid, which scrambled. Boy, I tell you, it was, you 
found yourself breathing hard. Okay, so you went

31:37.258 --> 31:39.421
up and you landed. What were the conditions when 
you landed at Kunming? I've seen some of the old

31:43.907 --> 31:46.951
pictures. There's an old one. Some old films that 
someone took right on the scene. Yeah, I can show

31:51.382 --> 31:53.567
you plenty of them. What were the conditions like 
at this era? The field at Kunming was a grass field,

31:56.754 --> 32:07.378
but it was a good 5,000 feet square, plus down one 
side of it, the eastern side of it, the Chinese

32:08.101 --> 32:19.376
coolies were building this huge, long, 5,000 
foot, about 300 foot wide runway in anticipation

32:08.101 --> 32:19.376
of bombers, you know, every bomber from the United 
States. And that just showed you how plans had been

32:19.777 --> 32:23.542
made. And it was a typical- Was that a stone runway? 
A typical Chinese construction, little broken up

32:27.387 --> 32:36.640
rocks by a Chinaman with a hammer. carried in 
baskets and dumped, and then following him was

32:36.940 --> 32:47.870
another guy with some pots with sloppy mud to pour 
on top of it, red clay. It would get hard. It'd be

32:49.611 --> 32:55.857
just, if you will, sort of a concrete mixture, and 
it made a stone runway, and it was about two feet

32:49.611 --> 32:55.857
thick. And that would hold a B-17 easy. As a matter 
of fact, B-17s and B-24s used that very well. They

33:03.724 --> 33:04.764
were building it then. We didn't use it. We used the 
grass off the side. They had our dormitories were

33:07.730 --> 33:12.815
just spotless. Each pilot had his own bunk. Just a 
little dormitory room, you know. But common.

33:19.601 --> 33:20.822
Everybody had their own little room? Everybody. 
By how large? My room was a little bit bigger than

33:24.646 --> 33:27.849
this. 12 by 12? Yeah, I'd say 12 by 12. I forget. 
Actually I'd say it was about nine by twelve. It was

33:38.961 --> 33:42.607
a cot, regular army type cot with a good mattress on 
it. Heated particularly at night in the coldest

33:45.071 --> 33:50.720
time. Well in the morning a little cooler, you'd 
come in about six o'clock with a charcoal brazier.

33:56.809 --> 33:58.592
That was heater room in the cold. We had lights. and 
common latrine facilities down the way. We had a

34:06.560 --> 34:17.950
common dining hall and a club, if you will, where 
the men and the officers, so-called officers and

34:06.560 --> 34:17.950
men, we had no real separation over there. This was 
some regulations and rules, very few, only an

34:17.970 --> 34:28.239
absolute medal had been put out by Chenault. I was a 
little bit surprised and wondering for a while how

34:30.374 --> 34:37.362
this thing was going to operate because there was 
no rules and regulations involved. You know,

34:37.382 --> 34:39.445
strictly military discipline then. And I was just 
wondering, and knowing what, having heard of

34:40.366 --> 34:50.037
mercenary outfits, I wondered, you know, maybe 
this is what this was. But it proved later on to me

34:50.057 --> 34:58.727
that we, in my opinion, the American Volunteer 
Group was not a mercenary outfit per se, I assure

34:50.057 --> 34:58.727
you. We were a well-trained, close-knit, 
extremely competent fighter group. What was the

35:10.007 --> 35:15.491
difference between a professional fighter group 
and a mercenary?

35:18.814 --> 35:26.961
The difference was ours was an outfit that held 
together and proved itself in combat. A mercenary

35:27.702 --> 35:29.203
outfit was from, if you will, civilian type 
commercial pilots, maybe one or two dishonorably

35:31.985 --> 35:55.362
discharged military type, maybe from Poland, 
Canada, one or two from the United States, even

35:31.985 --> 35:55.362
some Russian pilots with some beat up equipment, 
maybe some Chinese, I mean some Russian

35:31.985 --> 35:55.362
equipment, that just didn't hold together. We 
were a And like I told you recently, we were picked

35:59.575 --> 36:05.740
for the cream of the crop of the trained guys. How 
would you like to be, I put your question, how would

36:06.701 --> 36:10.084
you like to be a commander? You can't ask me a 
question. That's not fair. But I'm doing this

36:13.627 --> 36:16.169
rhetorically. And I'm a commander type of one. And 
I look back upon this. Here we are. Here is

36:22.675 --> 36:24.096
Chenault, the commander. And he just reaches out 
and picks trains very capably trained

36:30.727 --> 36:36.874
people for an air force. And then gives them an 
airplane, and he got made. Really, you would ask me

36:40.419 --> 36:42.101
about training a while ago? We didn't have a hell of 
a lot of training. We just indoctrinated each

36:43.322 --> 36:45.745
other. And then the problem was, of course, 
holding each other together. Well, and I

36:49.250 --> 36:59.502
actually- So that's the difference between 
mercenaries and- Okay, so you were really a

36:49.250 --> 36:59.502
well-trained group of professionals with 
outstanding equipment? To be the Chinese Air

37:02.171 --> 37:03.813
Force. Okay, okay. Now let's go back here. I want to 
ask you one question. We were talking about

37:07.798 --> 37:10.461
conditions, and you described your room. How 
about your food? The food,

37:13.364 --> 37:19.011
well, the food was good. As a matter of fact, it was 
American food, American-style food. Eggs, oh,

37:23.276 --> 37:25.539
eggs. We had, every once in a while they had fresh 
beef. And vegetables, you know, China, the

37:29.131 --> 37:33.135
Chinese have terrific vegetables. But chicken, 
they've got sick chicken in the line. We'd eat

37:37.759 --> 37:39.321
chicken morning, noon, and night. A lot of times I 
had fried chicken for breakfast. Really? Dude

37:41.743 --> 37:42.344
chicken. This was later on when it got a little bit 
difficult to get, during the war, got a little

37:42.604 --> 37:49.651
difficult to get other types of food. But 
generally speaking, the food was good, adequate.

37:54.255 --> 37:57.298
It was very good and adequate down in Burma. Well, 
what about... how you ate compared to how the

37:58.882 --> 38:03.369
average Kool-Aid or the average person ate? Oh, no 
comparison. We ate like, well we ate, actually,

38:04.410 --> 38:21.896
I'd say we probably ate better than the average, I 
know we did, we ate better than the average United

38:04.410 --> 38:21.896
States serviceman, let's say that rushed over to 
India or to Southwest Asia. We ate better. Because

38:25.160 --> 38:27.724
it was an established mass upon the Chinese

38:28.075 --> 38:34.586
logistic structure. They were already in place. 
And Len Leith was already shipping food over

38:36.609 --> 38:40.316
there. How'd you get along with your coolie? Did 
you have servants? Well, we had common servants.

38:47.528 --> 38:52.817
For instance, my little barber cut my hair for two 
cents. and we had to speak broken immediately we

38:53.185 --> 39:22.483
started you know broken Chinese and they'd pick up 
broken English we'd pick up broken Chinese and the

38:53.185 --> 39:22.483
cootie that would come in with my brazier in the 
morning he wouldn't even wake me up he'd just come

38:53.185 --> 39:22.483
in get the pot go out get the charcoal going and 
bring it back in and leave maybe I'd see him in the

38:53.185 --> 39:22.483
afternoon clean up the room we'd have paid them a 
cent the place was kept immaculate and laundry

39:23.122 --> 39:27.209
was, you know, you've always heard of Chinese 
laundromat. They did that every day, and we just,

39:27.229 --> 39:31.796
they'd pick it up. It was, in effect, we had 
homemade maids, and

39:32.797 --> 39:42.533
they provided the KP's for cooking. The grounds 
was kept neat, and the The structures were well

39:52.012 --> 40:00.020
built, plaster and- Did they serve you plaster and 
brick? Plaster, but adobe brick. Did the Chinese

40:03.604 --> 40:07.547
serve you when you ate dinner? Yes. Did they cook 
the food? They cooked the food and served it at the

40:09.169 --> 40:13.654
table just like an officer's club. As a matter of 
fact, we'd have a choice of menu of maybe two or

40:13.914 --> 40:17.838
three. Like in the morning we'd have eggs any 
style. Every once in a while they'd have a bacon

40:21.779 --> 40:30.329
that was sort of a local style bacon, but it tasted 
like bacon. Eventually we got American food and

40:31.211 --> 40:35.836
had American bacon. At lunch we'd have soup, 
always have soup. Sometimes have soup breakfast

40:41.443 --> 40:45.508
if you wanted to.

40:49.606 --> 40:51.288
Yeah, we got milk. I don't know where it came from, 
but at times we got milk and it was good.

40:58.758 --> 41:05.247
In between missions, did you ever have any time 
off, or was there a town nearby or anything? Yes,

41:05.267 --> 41:06.108
yes. And did you go into that town? How were you 
treated by the people? Yeah, we were in a town in the

41:09.613 --> 41:12.637
city of Kunming. Now Kunming, area-wise, is about 
the size of, let's say,

41:19.745 --> 41:25.493
geographic-wise and area-wise, say the size of 
Austin. But when I was there in the early part of the

41:25.513 --> 41:36.489
war, when some refugees had come into it, the 
population was about 400,000. We'd go into town,

41:38.451 --> 41:46.663
see we'd have regular training days, and about 
once a week we'd have a day off. had a few old jalopy

41:46.964 --> 42:12.718
type sedans that was at our disposal, and viewers 
would get together, go into town, and they had a

41:46.964 --> 42:12.718
theater with printed American, English 
subtitles, and very nice restaurants, some very

41:46.964 --> 42:12.718
nice restaurants, and other parts of the city of 
course over typical Far Eastern just pitifully

42:15.213 --> 42:26.309
poverty-stricken and bedraggled

42:15.213 --> 42:26.309
Chinese with eating on the sidewalk and streets 
were filthy, typical for East Sloan. And we'd buy

42:27.210 --> 42:38.927
maybe some satin coverlets to send home that you 
put over a, make a quilt with. Sure. Real satin,

42:39.668 --> 42:41.170
beautiful thing. with cars with sewn embroidered 
Chinese dragons on it. As a matter of fact, sent a

42:47.259 --> 42:49.162
lot of those. Pillowcases and things like that? 
Yeah. But other than that. Well, how'd you get

42:54.410 --> 42:56.513
along with the people when you went in? Our 
relations with the Chinese people were

42:56.754 --> 43:00.920
practically nil. Naturally, you know, driving in 
town, we had. A tragic time. Oh, yeah. And of

43:06.348 --> 43:10.735
course, driving down the street was the hardest 
thing in the world to get them out of your way. We

43:11.440 --> 43:13.502
continued on the horn. There were practically no 
vehicles in the city at all. Bicycles up to the zoo,

43:17.126 --> 43:24.854
but people mostly on foot.

43:25.255 --> 43:26.236
They knew who we were. The people really who minded 
to running the business of the city and the higher

43:27.437 --> 43:39.490
levels of Chinese population, they knew who we 
were and knew what our purpose was, and they loved

43:27.437 --> 43:39.490
us.

43:42.828 --> 43:56.438
The social stories were given by the governor, the 
mayor, some of the wealthier citizens, and some of

43:42.828 --> 43:56.438
us were invited for dinners. We didn't 
necessarily have to eat with chopsticks.

44:12.207 --> 44:15.652
We had our own, in effect, PX, if you will. It was 
small, as it was, but in a liquor store. To buy a

44:21.780 --> 44:35.177
bottle of liquor, I remember on Christmas Day in 
Chungking,

44:21.780 --> 44:35.177
yeah, no, Christmas Day in Kunming, I and two 
others paid $52 a barrel

44:42.987 --> 44:44.369
You were thirsty.

44:47.272 --> 44:51.918
That was George Burgoyne and Jim Costner again, 
the two I told you about. All three of us got in the

44:51.978 --> 44:57.265
same

44:51.978 --> 44:57.265
squadron. But every once in a while, the British 
would come in with a supply of liquor. And they were

45:01.831 --> 45:05.816
practically giving us for nothing, a ration. We 
lived comfortably. We had plenty of black

45:09.059 --> 45:10.421
clothing. And uniforms, there was no... What 
uniforms we... Well, we're going to get to

45:10.441 --> 45:17.371
uniforms and regulations. But before we do, when 
you went into town, did the people treat you well

45:17.451 --> 45:27.525
because they thought that you were there to defend 
them? Or how did they treat you? Well, our

45:29.427 --> 45:35.957
relations with the Chinese civilians, if you 
will, in town were, like I say, practically

45:29.427 --> 45:35.957
nailed. If we'd go into a store to buy something, 
communication-wise, English and Chinese, you

45:38.405 --> 45:42.430
know, we couldn't speak. Every once in a while, 
you'd run across one who would interpret, could

45:42.911 --> 45:46.355
speak a few words. But we'd haggle on prices, and 
generally they would give, just because of their

45:47.316 --> 45:58.571
respect for us, and they'd give us a terrific 
discount on something you would buy, for

45:47.316 --> 45:58.571
instance. Always gay and laughing, because they 
were happy, you know, these American heroes would

46:00.093 --> 46:08.243
come into my place and finish them. We were heroes 
to them, and particularly after we started

46:08.898 --> 46:14.565
shooting from our plant down. Now we became 
widespread heroes. Like Madam said, we were her

46:16.887 --> 46:21.373
little angels.

46:23.095 --> 46:24.176
They treated us well. I don't remember ever, ever 
any group, even when they're getting in maybe a

46:24.556 --> 46:37.892
drunken, two or three of them getting in a drunken 
riot, maybe in a local restaurant, never really

46:24.556 --> 46:37.892
any trouble coming from them.

46:41.787 --> 46:48.142
Whenever we'd go to a social gathering, it was 
similar to, let's say, one right here in the United

46:41.787 --> 46:48.142
States. It was just as nice a host and courteous and 
extremely happy to have us as guests.

46:57.344 --> 47:00.471
Some of them would, at times, we'd have an affair 
out at the base.

